# 🔧 Troubleshooting Guide

Common issues you might run into and how to fix them.

---

## ❌ PCs can't ping their default gateway

**Symptom:** `ping 10.10.10.1` fails from Admin-PC

**Checklist:**
- [ ] Is the PC's IP and gateway set correctly? (Desktop → IP Configuration)
- [ ] Is the access switch port in the correct VLAN?
  ```
  show vlan brief
  ```
- [ ] Is the SVI (VLAN interface) on the Core Switch up?
  ```
  show interface vlan 10
  ```
  Look for `Line protocol is up`. If it says `down`, make sure at least one access port in that VLAN is active and connected.

---

## ❌ Inter-VLAN routing not working (can't ping other VLANs)

**Symptom:** User-PC-1 can't ping Web-Server (different VLAN)

**Checklist:**
- [ ] Is `ip routing` enabled on the Core Switch?
  ```
  show running-config | include ip routing
  ```
  If missing, run: `ip routing`

- [ ] Do all SVIs have the correct IP and are they `no shutdown`?
  ```
  show ip interface brief
  ```

- [ ] Is the trunk link between the Core Switch and access switch carrying the right VLANs?
  ```
  show interfaces trunk
  ```
  The "VLANs allowed and active" column should list your VLANs (10, 20, 30).

---

## ❌ ACL is blocking traffic it shouldn't

**Symptom:** Users can't reach the web server even on port 80

**Check the ACL hit counters:**
```
show ip access-lists USERS-TO-SERVERS
```
Look at the match counts to see which line is being hit.

**Common mistakes:**
- ACL is applied on the wrong interface or direction (`in` vs `out`)
- The `permit` statement for port 80 has a typo (use `eq 80` not `eq www` in older IOS)
- There's a `deny` before the `permit` — ACLs are read top to bottom, first match wins

**Fix:** Remove and re-apply the ACL in the correct order:
```
no ip access-list extended USERS-TO-SERVERS

ip access-list extended USERS-TO-SERVERS
 permit tcp 10.10.20.0 0.0.0.255 10.10.30.0 0.0.0.255 eq 80
 permit tcp 10.10.20.0 0.0.0.255 10.10.30.0 0.0.0.255 eq 443
 deny   ip 10.10.20.0 0.0.0.255 10.10.30.0 0.0.0.255
 permit ip any any
```

